When precision is crucial, an extra term should be included in (1.89) to account for the overlap between the gate and source junction, incorporating the fringing capacitance (due to boundary effects). This additional component is

$$
\begin{equation*}
C_{o v}=W L_{o v} C_{o x} \tag{1.90}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $L_{\mathrm{ov}}$ is the effective overlap distance, typically derived empirically ${ }^{15}$. Consequently,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{gs}}=\frac{2}{3} \mathrm{WLC}_{\mathrm{ox}}+\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{ov}} \tag{1.91}
\end{equation*}
$$

Key Point: In a MOSFET, the predominant parasitic capacitance is $\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{gs}}$, proportional to the gate area WL and inversely proportional to oxide thickness via $\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{ox}}$, especially when higher accuracy is required.
